00:01:31.560 --> 00:01:33.687
That's the two currents in our devices.

00:01:33.687 --> 00:01:37.122
Now, gonna use Kirchhoff's
Current Law on this node

00:01:37.122 --> 00:01:39.744
right here, and that says
that all the currents

00:01:39.744 --> 00:01:43.673
flying out of that node
have to add up to zero.

00:01:43.673 --> 00:01:44.827
So let's do that.

00:01:44.827 --> 00:01:47.577
Let's say iC plus iR equals zero.

00:01:52.477 --> 00:01:55.560
