00:08:53.627 --> 00:08:55.829
And there's a time when we do know that.

00:08:55.829 --> 00:08:57.293
And that is t equals zero.

00:08:57.293 --> 00:09:01.675
At t equals zero we know that
the battery was hooked up

00:09:01.675 --> 00:09:04.242
and there's a bunch of
charge on the capacitor

00:09:04.242 --> 00:09:07.294
so we know that the
voltage on the capacitor

00:09:07.294 --> 00:09:10.211
at time zero, is equal to V naught.

00:09:13.275 --> 00:09:15.452
So now we have a pair of variables here.

00:09:15.452 --> 00:09:17.441
We know v and t at the same time, so let's

00:09:17.441 --> 00:09:20.015
plug that into our
proposed solution and see

00:09:20.015 --> 00:09:21.182
how k pops up.

00:09:25.363 --> 00:09:28.200
So we're gonna put these two
into our proposed solution

00:09:28.200 --> 00:09:30.891
and see what happens to k.

00:09:30.891 --> 00:09:35.383
V, at time equals zero,
is V naught, and that's

00:09:35.383 --> 00:09:39.133
equal to k times e to
the minus t, minus zero

00:09:43.179 --> 00:09:45.012
at time zero, over RC.

00:09:47.159 --> 00:09:50.742
Now this whole expression
is e to the zero,

00:09:52.455 --> 00:09:53.911
or one.

00:09:53.911 --> 00:09:57.049
So it drops out of the expression

00:09:57.049 --> 00:10:00.049
and all we get is k equals V naught.

00:10:01.222 --> 00:10:04.805
K is the starting
voltage on the capacitor.

00:10:06.424 --> 00:10:09.896
And that gives us to our
final answer, which is

00:10:09.896 --> 00:10:13.313
v of t equals V naught, starting voltage,

00:10:16.669 --> 00:10:19.002
e to the minus time over RC.

00:10:28.434 --> 00:10:30.371
We can go one small step
further and find out

00:10:30.371 --> 00:10:31.621
what is i of t.

00:10:34.051 --> 00:10:37.301
Well, i of t is equal to v of t over R,

00:10:40.067 --> 00:10:43.266
that's just Ohm's Law, and so i of t

00:10:43.266 --> 00:10:47.349
equals V naught over R,
e to the minus t over RC.

00:10:54.363 --> 00:10:58.073
That is the natural
response of an RC circuit.

